article.headline: Wis.-Green Bay 92, Chicago St. 81
article.story: GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Mike Schachtner scored a career-high 36 points, Ryan Evanochko had a career-high 16 assists and Wisconsin-Green Bay tied a school record with 14 3-pointers in a 92-81 victory over Chicago State Tuesday night. Schachtner, a sophomore, finished 11-of-15 from the field and 7-of-7 at the line to nearly double his previous career high of 19 points, set two weeks ago at Fairleigh Dickinson. He hit 7-of-8 3-pointers to help the Phoenix match the 14 3-pointers they made Feb. 27, 2005, at Wright State. Evanochko, a senior, topped his Horizon League-best average of five assists by late in the first half. He broke his previous career best of 14 assists set last season in the conference tournament against Illinois-Chicago. He also had 14 points. Green Bay (4-5) won a second straight game, while Chicago State (4-8) lost for the fifth time in its last six games despite 32 points from David Holston. Schachtner hit four 3-pointers in the first six minutes of the second half, as Green Bay opened a 58-41 lead, but when he left to take a breather Chicago State came right back. Holston scored 11 straight points for the Cougars, including three 3-pointers, and Michael Hendersons tip-in pulled Chicago State within 60-56 with 11 minutes left. Schachtner re-entered the game and combined with Evanochko on a 9-0 run to make it 77-63 with 6:32 left. Schachtner hit a 3-pointer and four free throws during the run. Chicago State made one last charge, getting within 85-78 on three free throws by Holston with 1:31 to go, but Schachtner made a 3-point play on a fast break and added two free throws to make it 90-78 with just over a minute left. Schachtner's 36 points were the most by a Phoenix player since Jeff Nordgaard scored 37 on Feb. 22, 1996, at Illinois-Chicago. Evanochko's 16 assists were the second-most by a Green Bay player in program history, behind the 19 by Frank Nardi on Feb. 24, 1986, against Northern Iowa.
